## 5. WRITING PRODUCT SPECS

### 5.1 The PRD (Product Requirements Document)

A PRD is a thinking tool, not a contract. It exists to align the team and surface disagreements early.

**Structure:**

```markdown
# [Feature Name] — Product Spec

## Status
[ ] Draft  [ ] In Review  [ ] Approved  [ ] Shipped

## Problem
One paragraph. What problem are we solving? For whom? How do we know it's real?
No solution language here.

## User
Who specifically? One primary user type. Be precise.
"Mid-market engineering managers at B2B SaaS companies, 20–200 person orgs, who
own the tooling budget but don't write code day-to-day."

## Jobs To Be Done
When [situation], I want to [motivation], so I can [outcome].

## Evidence
- User quotes (verbatim, with source)
- Quantitative signals (support tickets, drop-off data, NPS comments)
- Competitive signals
- Internal observation

## Success Metrics
Primary:   [one metric that proves this worked]
Secondary: [1–2 supporting signals]
Guardrail: [metric that must not regress]

## Scope (This Version)
What is included. What is explicitly excluded. Why.

## Solution
The proposed approach. Not the only approach — the chosen one and why.
Include: mocks / flows / edge cases / error states / empty states

## Open Questions
- [Question] → Owner → Due date
List things you don't know yet that could affect the decision.

## Out of Scope / Future Consideration
Things you chose not to do and why. This prevents scope creep later.
```

### 5.2 Writing Standards

- **Problem statement first, always.** If someone reads only the first paragraph, they should understand why this matters.
- **Use real user quotes.** They are more persuasive than your summary of what users said.
- **Be explicit about tradeoffs.** "We chose X over Y because Z." Not just "we're doing X."
- **Name your assumptions.** "This assumes users check the dashboard daily. If that's wrong, the design breaks."
- **One primary metric.** Two primary metrics means no primary metric.
- **Specs should shrink over time.** A good spec gets tighter with every revision, not longer.

